# capabilities analysis # a2: the program first identifies the distribution of the parameters by using the kolmogorov-smirnov test for goodness-of-fit. import numpy as np import pandas as pd from scipy import stats import warnings warnings.filterwarnings("ignore") # importing data from excel data = pd.read_excel("d:\asq\exels\project 5 data.xlsx") # selecting quality parameters sample_data = data.iloc[0:30] quality_parameter = sample_data.columns # list of distribution types to test list_of_dists = ['alpha', 'logistic', 'dweibull', 'expon', 'exponnorm', 'weibull_min', 'weibull_max', 'norm', 'johnsonsb', 'johnsonsu', 'genextrem', 'lognorm', 'pearson3'] # looping through each quality parameter for j in np.arange(1, 16, 1): par = sample_data.iloc[:, j] results = [] # testing each distribution type for i in list_of_dists: dist = getattr(stats, i) # statistics parameter for each distribution type param = dist.fit(par) a = stats.kstest(par, i, args=param) # ks test results.append((i, a[0], a[1])) results.sort(key=lambda x: float(x[2]), reverse=true) y = pd.dataframe(results, columns=["distribution type", "ks-test", "p-value"]) y = round(y, 3) # displaying the results for each quality parameter print(j, quality_parameter[j], y) nor = y[y['distribution type'] == 'norm'] # if normal distribution if nor.iloc[0, 2] > 0.05: z = (nor.iloc[0, 0], nor.iloc[0, 2]) print('normal distribution with p-value', z) # if non-normal distribution elif y.iloc[0, 2] > 0.05: z = (y.iloc[0, 0], y.iloc[0, 2]) print('non-normal distribution -', z) # if binomial method is to be used else: print('binomial method') 1

to prepare the histogram for the two groups and calculate the mean and standard deviation, we can use python programming language and its data analysis libraries such as numpy and matplotlib. here's the python code to accomplish this: ```python import numpy as np import matplotlib.pyplot as plt # group a data group_a = [82, 76, 89, 84, 69, 77, 84, 95, 89, 84] # group b data group_b = [77, 88, 70, 85, 90, 83, 83, 76, 94, 83] # calculate mean and standard deviation for group a mean_a = np.mean(group_a) std_a = np.std(group_a) # calculate mean and standard deviation for group b mean_b = np.mean(group_b) std_b = np.std(group_b) # plotting the histograms plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6)) # histogram for group a plt.hist(group_a, bins=10, alpha=0.5, label='group a') plt.axvline(mean_a, color='r', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='mean a') plt.xlabel('scores') plt.ylabel('frequency') plt.title('histogram - group a') plt.legend() plt.show() # histogram for group b plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6)) plt.hist(group_b, bins=10, alpha=0.5, label='group b') plt.axvline(mean_b, color='r', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='mean b') plt.xlabel('scores') plt.ylabel('frequency') plt.title('histogram - group b') plt.legend() plt.show() # print mean and standard deviation for both groups print('group a - mean:', mean_a) print('group a - standard deviation:', std_a) print('group b - mean:', mean_b) print('group b - standard deviation:', std_b) ``` the code above will generate two histograms, one for group a and one for group b, along with vertical dashed lines indicating the mean score for each group. it will also print the mean and standard deviation for both groups. you can run this code in a python environment, such as jupyter notebook or google colab, to visualize the histograms and obtain the mean and standard deviation values for each group. 1

# copiar y pegar en jupyter lab de python %matplotlib inline import numpy as np import matplotlib.pyplot as plt from scipy.special import erfc from ipywidgets import interact, floatslider # parámetros t_c=926 # temperatura en °c d0=2*10**(-5) # constante c en fe fcc en m2/s q=142000 # energia activación c en fe fcc en j/mol d = d0*np.exp(-q/(8.314*(t_c+273))) # coeficiente de difusión c0 = 0.2 # concentración inicial cs = 1.3 # concentración en la superficie # crear una matriz de distancias x = 0.001*np.linspace(0, 2, 1000) # función para calcular y graficar la concentración para un tiempo dado def plot_concentration(t=0.01): c = c0 + (cs - c0) * erfc(x / (2 * np.sqrt(d * t))) plt.plot(x*1000, c) plt.ylim(0, 1.5) plt.xlabel("distancia (mm)", fontname="verdana", size=12) plt.ylabel("% carbono", fontname="verdana", size=12) plt.show() # crear un slider para el tiempo y usarlo para interactuar con la función de graficación interact(plot_concentration, t=floatslider(min=0.01, max=50000.0, step=500, value=0.01)); 1

#6 syawal 1444h fisika fmipa unej import numpy as np import coolingroutine as cr import matplotlib.pyplot as plt #%matplotlib inline times = np.linspace(0, 20, 201) #kasus ke 1 temps_beforecooling = cr.cube_before_cooling(times, **cr.cooling_parameters) plt.plot(times, temps_beforecooling) plt.xlabel('time (min)') plt.ylabel('coffee temperature (degrees celcius)') plt.show() #kasus ke 2 temps_aftercooling = cr.cube_after_cooling(times, **cr.cooling_parameters) plt.plot(times, temps_aftercooling) plt.xlabel('time (min)') plt.ylabel('coffee temperature (degrees celcius)') plt.show() #kasus ke 3 temps_cont = cr.continuous_sugar_cooling(times, **cr.cooling_parameters) plt.plot(times, temps_cont) plt.xlabel('time (min)') plt.ylabel('coffee temperature (degrees celcius)') plt.show() #kasus ke 4 temps_n = cr.sugar_specifiedtime_cooling(times, [50, 100, 150], **cr.cooling_parameters) plt.plot(times, temps_n) plt.xlabel('time (min)') plt.ylabel('coffee temperature (degrees celcius)') plt.show() #kasus ke 5 plt.plot(times, temps_beforecooling, label='cube before cooling') plt.plot(times, temps_aftercooling, label='cube after cooling') plt.plot(times, temps_cont, label='continuous') plt.plot(times, temps_n, label='3 times of dropping cube') plt.xlabel('time (min)') plt.ylabel('coffee temperature (degrees celcius)') plt.legend() plt.show() 1
